\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid3230341 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. I was born in Water Lane. R
otherham. And there was only about four houses. I can't tell you number like. It was on the water - on the canal side, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How many years did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh - well I was born there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you live there until you were married or did you move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
I don't remember moving from there from me being a girl, big girl you know. I weren't married, no. And then I got married. I got married in Rotherham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you got married were your parents still living at Water Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, I lived in Beryl Street when I got married. Yes. Westgate, Rotherham.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember how old you would be when you moved from Water Lane to Beryl Street? Was it while you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes, 'cos I went - we was going to the school from th
ere, I went to Alma Road Board School in Rotherham, and me husband went to the same school and that's where I got to know him, got associated with one another you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember about how old you would be when you moved from Water Lane to Beryl Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Well - I was eighteen when I was married out of Beryl Street. I should be around about - as near as I can tell you about fifteen. And I got married there, at me mother's you see, at bottom of Beryl Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember why your parents moved from Water Lane to Beryl Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I don't remember 'em moving. Only from - Water Lane to Beryl Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember why they moved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well it was a bigger house. You see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 
This was very small at Waterside, and this one was three bedroom house, it was a new one. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
That was on the river - the canal side. And mother moved right into other one, but she stayed there and me dad died - while he died. Then I got courting - my - my husband and then we got married you see. Register Office at Rotherham.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Well as far as I know, I had three brothers older than me. And I'd one sister, I think - I think she is living. I can't be sure but I've only seen her twice since I've come to Keighley, and t
hat's forty odd years. But she's been bedridden for a long while. And her daughter lives at Wyeth on Durn and - I keep trying to mention it, you know, I forget you know, I get talking I forget, but I don't think there's anything happened to her. But - she
'
s a daughter and she's a son and - me daughter was - I don't know whether - well it's just outskirts - outskirts of Mexwell where I come from, and I don't there's anything happened to her 'cos I think my daughter'd let me known. I had three brothers and t
wo sisters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you have any brothers or sisters younger than yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh no, the three brothers were all - brothers were I - me mother had seven boys }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 after}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  she'd me. She had eleven. And she'd seven boys afore me. Well the three - there was thre
e of them, one were called - me oldest brother we call him Frederick, we used to call him Fred and then there were Joseph, and then there were Thomas. And then I come next and me sisters next, our Elizabeth. And then there were twins, she had twins at cha
n
ge of life and they both - one lived to be nine month old and the other lived to be fifteen month old. They both died, yes. And there was - before me oldest brother's what's - what was living like - she actually - beside him but they're dead, they died yo
ung, right young - I don't - I don't remember a lot about them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Your mother never told you what they died from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well - there was one - and our Fred, he was vaccinated but - him - him that died - oldest one - and he died through vaccination. Vacci
nation - you do it - do it after anyone, not like they do now, and used to be four big marks on your arm, I have four. Well - when he were - wasn't much in our William and him, I remember we used to have one of them old fashioned - old fashioned house she
 
lived in and she'd one of them all round - what they call it, with three - three legs on 'em. They put 'em up chimney, on a hook. Like a - a - like a - forget what they call it, like a saucepan you know, it would go up chimney and - you know boil your wat
e
r up. That's right. And - and - of course there were not like there is now then. Well, she took this pan right down - what she's told me like - that he took it - she took it right down to bottom of garden so he wouldn't get scalded. There was something in
 
she wanted. So our Willie, we used to call him Willie - called him William but called him Willie for short, he goes down to play gown bottom of garden and he fell with his - bottom - backside right into pan. Well - oh it pulled the skin up, Willie died sh
ock of it. And that's all I remember then. I can remember my brother dying, my oldest brother dying, I was only a girl.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 That was Fred was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. And he - he was vaccinated after somebody else, I was going to tell you, after somebody else. Well
 that caused him to have epileptic fits. Yes it did. I can remember that as if it were now. And used to have a - he used to have fits up in street, he couldn't work. But they had centres, you understand. And - where have we got now? Oh that was in Rotherh
a
m. And - Mrs Richardson, what laid 'em and washed him out - she put him on a table, they had him on his feet, they never come out of door. And she said, oh he's dead Mrs Burton. So she said, oh he never is. She said, oh he is, I'll have to wash and lay hi
m
 out. Wash and lay him, put him under window. So - me mother won't go to bed that night and I won't go to bed without her, they called me after me mother. And me dad kept shouting down, come on lass, come to bed, he said, it's late, it's twelve o'clock. S
he said, it isn't twelve o'clock. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 
She says, go on, we're all right, me and our Alice is all right - and I weren't very old - I can remember it a lot, and - he said, well come on then, he said, you can't make no better on it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 He said, he's dead and he's gone
. So our - our Bessie says - me mother says, I'll come when that clock strikes twelve, the old parish church in Rotherham, and she did and I did, I stuck with her. Well all at once that - that church bell, we could hear it, all silent at night you know, }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 quiet,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 well we didn't live like over long way off it, and - all at once - the sheet - sheet move. And - went like that, and he lowered himself up and sat onto table. Oh I couldn't tell you about a shock we got. And me mother says, oh Alice, she says, look at
 our Fred. Oh, she said, look at him, he's come to life, he's not been dead. So I said, never mind mother, I said, he'll be all right. So she gets up, goes to him and she gets a blanket and puts blanket round him, wraps him up, sits him on her knee in the
 
rocking chair, they were rocking chairs them days you know, and she were rocking him. Well I was sit there - I was stuck to chair, I couldn't move. So I shouts, dad, come on down, I says, look sharp. He said, I've tell you to come to bed. He couldn't real
i
ze it you know. I said, will you come down? He said - oh - Good God, he said, whatever's the matter with you? She said it's our Fred, he's come to life, look. Well he'd been wasted twenty-four hours, yes. So, she says - mother says to him, go and fetch Mr
s Richardson what laid him out, you know who it is the top road. And - 'course I weren't married like, I was a young - and - she said - oh he went for her and she come back and she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 wait}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 , what's the matter Mrs Burton? Oh, she says, look here Mrs Richardson s
he said, me little lad's come back to life. Well she was took - she didn't know what - what to think. So she says to me dad says, get ready George, she said, and go and fetch doctor. Well he whipped }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 up }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 and put his clothes and that on, he comes down the sta
irs, now, he says, I'll go for Doctor - Doctor Corrison. So - anyway - so - me - me mother says to Mrs Richardson, stop with me a bit won't you? She said, oh I will, I won't leave you - while doctor's been. So he went for doctor, doctor brought him back i
n
 his car with being late at night you know to come back, and when he came in - oh I've never seen a doctor turn his face - turn it - I couldn't tell you what he looked like. So - anyway - took blanket off him and examined him, so he say - you're - and a r
i
ght beautiful lad he was - so he says - well, she says, I'm a doctor, he said, I've been to some cases, but - he said, I've never seen a - never seen a thing like this. And he'd been in a trance twenty-four hours. His head was cold and everything. Well he
 
says, I can't - I'll never forget this, he said, no and I won't doctor. I says, I know it upset me and me mother. He said, well it will do. He said - I know it's upset me, he says. But anyway, he says, I'll - I've something too special on, I'll come back.
 
So he came back and he brought us some to stuff to take. Now keep him wrapped up warm, says the - and do what you can for him, he said, and he'll go on all right. It's a - it's a - what they call a - a - he was in a trance for twenty-four hours. And when 
he went in his fit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 he said our Father which art in heaven, he said his prayer. And he always used to say that before he went in 'em, that's why we used to know he was going in his fit you see. Eeh and he were a strapping big young fellow.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he live then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
He - oh he lived to be twenty-four. He died when he were twenty-four years old. And - it was - it used to - sometimes he - it used to vary, you know, and I could tell, and I used to sleep with him. In me mother's room and me father's room. The
re's only mum - me as he would take to or me mum, and when he were going in 'em he used to get hold of your hand like that, squeezing, Our Father which art in heaven and then drop off. And I could tell in a minute. And then we always used to keep a little
 
glimmer on the gas jet, they were gas jets then, purpose for him so we could watch him. So I said, ooh mum, go to our Fred, I says, I can't loosen me hand. So she says - wait a minute. She got out of bed and - dad got out of bed. So - she says, now Fred, 
come on, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 there\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 a good lad. Come on, she says, you'll get better. Come on, she said to him. All at once he went. And that there lad's hand were on my wrist when he died - when - well, near on it practically. It had when he started be right poorly and I jus
t - you know - I couldn't get me wrist away. That's when he died that. About twenty-four when he died.
