then. And I went over to see him, well they sent for me, and - the woman that washed and laid him out said, there's one person he wants to see Mrs Burton. She said, who's that? Said, Alice. She's at Mexworth, she said, and don't I know. She says, 'cos he'
l
l not get - but he'd dropsy, all his legs - water running out of his legs, he had to be propped up at side of bed. And - that's him that worked at steel - he worked at steel place. We've all been workers, we've all been a family that worked. And - they co
m
e for me, me sister come for me 'cos she were at home then and she says, you want to come and see me dad Alice, she says, as I've been - mum's sent me for you, said they don't think he'll get better. So I - my boss said, what's the matter? 'Cos of being d
e
af he couldn't hear what she was saying you see. I says, she wants me to go and see me dad, she says it's all over with him. He said, well get there coat on and your hat, get hold of this he said and go and see him. So I come straight away back with her. 
W
ell when I went in - 'cos I - I'd children steps and stairs you know what I mean, somebody stopped and they looked after 'em for me and - when I went to this I stood at side of bed, packed up with pillows and and a bed rest, a bath here put his feet in. O
h
 - I said, mother, I said, what you send for me for now. Well, she said, I didn't like Alice, I don't, 'cos you've all them little kiddies and you've enough on your plate without - tearing around. Well I should have been worse if you hadn't have sent for 
me before he died. So anyway - he - I put me arms round him and he cocked his head up and I said, hello dad. Any better? He shook his head like that, he says, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 wanted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
