\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 He was seventy when he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 And they'd had about six children before you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 It'd be about I think - beg pardon? I - no, not afore they had me. Me mother you mean? No, she had three. Wait a minute.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But she had three that died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She - the first three, well they died. And then comes - our Fred. Th
ere were Willie, I don't remember the two 'cos I was only a girl then, not very old. There was our Willie and there was t'other two, then our Fred, Frederick he come the oldest of all three boys. And then there were George and then there were Thomas, then
 - me mother had four girls. She had seven boys but the youngest, in the first beginning having children, she buried them you see. She buried them others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So when they had you they'd been married quite a few years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes, yes. Well I married when I was eighteen so I'll leave you to guess.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So they must have been in their thirties when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh - no - yes, round about - that'd do I think. As near as I can tell you it is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Where did he come from, your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Now I coul
dn't tell you but Rotherham man. But me mother come from Worcester. Yes, she were a Worcestershire woman, he were a - he was a Rotherham man. As far as I'm concerned, I never hear mention owt like - about affairs like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What was his occupation, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Well - the whole four, no, three, our Joseph, our Fred - our - George and our - they all worked at Steel Peach and Tozers, in steel trade, they were in steel trade, and me dad were. Well I worked in same place where he used to work at. I were t
ipping rings for shells in 1918. Night work. When they bombed Sheffield. I can remember all that. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Your father worked at Steel Peach and Tozers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, he did, they all - they all worked there - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your father always work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, he never worked at pit. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 He worked there from being a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. Yes. As far as I'm concerned he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you know what he did in the steelworks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well like a labourer. Down in this 'ere kind of a lift. It's underground somewhere, just a labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he ever do any casual or part time jobs in addition to his own work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. No. I never knew. He always worked at foundry, I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. No, but poor wages then. Mother only got half a sovereign of him every week. Golden sovereign - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  a sovereign. Yes, every week. Never got any more. I never had a big wage off my husband.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She brought five children up on half a sovereign a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She did. Yes. But m
ind you, she were in a biggish house and she used to have men lodgers. Now she - she would - do all for 'em - but keep 'em, she'd fetch what they wanted and she'd cook it and she used to wash for 'em, but she couldn't run a - she got getting older you kno
w, she were eighty-two when she died, and she was just always the same, you never see'd her no different. And they stuck wi' her for years. They did, they thought world - thought the world of my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 They were bachelors who lived with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh 
- do you mean - oh yes. One come from Birmingham. And then a lodger, he were lame, used to go away - with crutches - used to do for soldiers in war time, 1918, he used to go and clean the potatoes and suchlike, do a bit of job like that, bit of spending m
oney you know, and he were good to mother. He were very good to mother, fetching like her coal up and - little bit of jobs like that what were - '}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 cos}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  she neither drank nor smoked and she could save. She could.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you know how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
When I were born? No, but I got a pram and first time I went out in it I fell out of it. Me brother took me for a walk and - me dad says, if it's a girl, he said, I'll buy her a pram. I never forget it, I think of all them little ditti
es, I can't - and - he said, if it's a little girl, he said, I'll buy her a pram. So I was a little lass, mother'd seven lads afore she'd me. So anyway, it were then be a - with two handles on, one at each side you know, like a twin carrying pram, it stoo
d up like that with big wheels, you know, old fashioned style. Well Joseph, he took me out, oh they were itching to get me out, me mother tell me all this, she said, now Joe goes that way, he says I'm going to bring her back. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 She said, don't let nowt happen
 to her, she said, her dad'll kill me. So anyway - he took me out, he took on Camphill Road, and - me sister lived on there, she used to work at a brewery, well I worked at a brewery and all - in me time, and - he took me out and he got nearly to road end
 - and he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 
ried to get me down this - bit of a step like cross the edge, he gets me down, poor old Alice come wobbling out. So what me mother tell me, somebody pick me up and put me in me pram and he asked him where I lived. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Said - she lives - we live down 
Water Lane, lives down Water Lane where I were born, so anyway, they pushed pram up to top of lane, her said, you could go steady down there now and don't upset her again. She's all right. So }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  had - he had to tell me mother, so when he got home he says, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 Mam}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
, I've had baby out of pram. She says, what you been doing? He said, I catch on across side. He weren't very old but he - could tell tales you know. So anyway she says, didn't I tell you? And me dad comes, what's he been doing now? That's as he talked t
o him. He says, I'll not do it no more dad, he says, he says, I couldn't help it, he says, the wheel twisted onto cross he said, and she come out and a lady picked her up and brought me to top of lane. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 He said - he says, I'll kill you - he says. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I'm not going to take her out no more, I get scolded over it. I've laughed many an hour about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Your mother came from Worcester?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Worcester, yes. She were a chain maker. Yes, she used to work with her own father A chain mill. Chain miller. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 Chain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 A small mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Big - well, a biggish 'un. Yes. She come off well to do parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She worked in the mill with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, she used to carry a board and this 'ere - stuff on her head. On top of her head, yes, it were right }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 soft}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 . She used to have to carry what they call }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 a hod}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
. Like a bricklayer. Yes. And she used to - go up these steps to kiln, to big chimney you know, and there's a bung hole where you put 'em through and there's a man inside and puts - stacks 'em all up to dry, you see. Well she
 made them, she - all her life she were a chain maker. Well up to her - getting wed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She made chains?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Chains, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She did that until she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, done it ever since she were a girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did she do any jobs after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh no. She only more or less had like a boarding house you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She never did any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh no, not that I know anything -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You don't know how old she would be when you were born do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No I don't - I don't know how old. How old what - I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How old your mother was when she had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I couldn't tell you, she - she'd had three boys - she'd all them boys - seven boys - before me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So she must have been in her thirties when she had you mustn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Round about twenty-eight - or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You say she was going through the change when she had those twins?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. And the doctor said she'd had them twins at change of life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 And you were a few years old then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. I was only a bit of a girl like you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Could you tell me how many rooms there were in the house at Beryl Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, there was - sitting room, living room, off - off kitchen and a - three bed - was there three or was there four - four bedr
ooms. Yes, well like - one made into a bedroom. Three biggish bedrooms. There was two at back and one at the front. And then at side - facing the river, it were like a - a box affair. Like a - put a good bed in and - table and things. Well an old gentlema
n used to sleep in there when mother - room like, him that had the sticks, 'cos he - with getting up and down you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121  upstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  you had three big bedrooms and a little bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 And down stairs you had a sitting room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Had a sitting room and a - a biggish kitchen - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Was it a kitchen-cum-dinning room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. It was a - it was a - no one - practically - well nobody else had lived in it. It was new property - house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you have a kitchen and a dining room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 It was cellar kitchen downstairs. With a - to hang us washing out in like a back yard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You used to have about three lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your mother ever pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. Never, no. We had to do that as we got older.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Was the washing done at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. Did all us work at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your mother or father mend or make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Clothes? No. They used to keep theirself in that. All as they had was a breakfast. That - that - she used to give 
bed and breakfast, that's all. Used to buy their own - she used to wash for them, their shirts and like. But didn't keep 'em, she never kept 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But did your mother used to make your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. She bought me me clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did she used to mend them for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes. Oh if you got a little hole she'd put a patch on. She - she wouldn't destroy nothing like. Very careful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you hand your clothes down from one to the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh - yes, yes, if they were too little for me pass 'e
m over to my - sister. Well it were just same with boys you see 'cos some of 'em were like our Fred - our Joseph, he were stiff - you know, and next - next to my George, well he died in several - in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 sanatorium}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 sanatorium}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
. You know, what they call a bit - went queer, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 courting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 a young girl, she - he courted her twelve year, and she went away down into Somerset where - on munitions. Somebody telled him next morning she'd died, he went mad, he - oh - couldn't hardly walk, nerves and all the lot went. He was s
ix - over six foot. He come up with mother's shoes on - pair of mother's shoes. A lovely lad, never drank nor nowt. I've got some good - had some good family altogether, we've all - always kept ourselves together, understand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So your mother would buy new clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But when they got a bit too small for you your sister would have them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 We had to - we had to do that you know what I mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Were you ever given secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Secondhand clothes? Not as I know on, n
o. Well her's bought 'em. If there's been a good thing she - I'll buy that, you see what I mean, because we couldn't afford to - 'cos me dad only give her ten shilling a week. I told you about half a sovereign. That's all she got and she never got ha'port
h
 more, but made her - the reason, that's why she had to have somebody to help her, the lodger you see, well it used to help her with her rent and her coal and - 'cos it were like - well he'd bring his wages but the wages were practically were nothing then
 you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Do you remember where your mother used to buy your clothes, was there a particular shop that you used to go to buy new dressed and coats and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well more or less - for boys she used to go to pawn shop. A pawnshop like, they called
 it Whiskers, 'cos they used to sell suits and secondhand suits, they'd been pawned and good suits been - held up and she's had to buy 'em like that you see, for being cheap. But as for me I couldn't tell you what did for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You don't remember her going to the pawnshop for your dresses or coats or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh no. No. I don't remember, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you used to get new shoes or would they be secondhand?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well tell you the truth used to be glad of anybody giving us a pair then. Yes. Yes. And
 me mother were one of these sorts of you know, she never bothered with anybody, with neighbours, she always kept herself to herself. She weren't - you know - no, she wasn't like - she never went in nobody's house, she wouldn't go in telling tales like an
d
 suchlike that. She never made a - a practice of doing that. And she always used to say, and you won't, and I never did. I says, I won't mother don't you worry. She says, no, she says, you won't want to do. She didn't believe in 'cos she said there's some
body catching out, their calling somebody, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When your shoes became worn would your father repair them for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Me brother used to do. Me brother Joe, he'd - 'cos me dad were bad with his eyes and all and he used, to, let's look at the sh
oes Alice, do they want mending. And we used to have this foot with two, you know. Come on, take 'em off, I'll mend 'em for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 thee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 . Oh he was very good our Joe as a lad. They all were good to me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 In Rotherham did people have shoes just for weekends and wear clogs in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You never had clogs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
No. Only had clogs when I worked at mill here. I bought a secondhand pair of clogs. Well they were nearly new like and they got too little for her so she says would I have them. So
 I give her something - I just forget what I give her, I said, no I don't want 'em given us, I said, I'll give you something as you wont throw them away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. The boys have to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You can never remember your father doing any cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What about cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, not - boil some water make himself a drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would he do any washing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, he never did no housework.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he make fires for her in the morning before he went to work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. I don't remember him making a fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he ever do any decorating in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Or repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I used to decorate. I can paper wi' anybody. Well I used to help me mother like, used t
o help with odd bits of things like. All me daughters can paper their own home. Never have a decorator in. Paint and lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When any repairs needed doing to the house would your father do them? If a handle was coming off a door or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh he might do anything like that. If it were like easy job to do as what he could do he would do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But he wouldn't do any improvements, would he ever do anything to improve the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh if he thought he could get it right he would do. Oh he'd have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 try}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 . Yes, oh aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Can you ever remember your father helping look after you when you were children by dressing you or undressing you or bathing you or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he ever read to you or tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. No, just on his own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, mother'd take me out but not him. He just used to sit around you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he ever look after you when she was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 If she were poorly or anything like that - like - she were
 off colour like he'd say, now - don't go in there, your mother's poorly, not well. She went like that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would he ever let her go out and take over, would he ever say, I'll look after the children and you go out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh well she - she were never one to going out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 
I never known her to have been at pictures - well - silent pictures and all suchlike as that - theatre - never known my mother to go in a music hall, all the time I can remember being a mother. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She never went out - she worked in her
 own home and she never bothered wi' a neighbour. Speak to 'em, she'd do owt for 'em, but she never made a practice of being neighbours. 'Cos they weren't neighbours them days - art of 'em - part of 'em wasn't. I told you after she got married she keep he
rself to herself and she did do, and she made us do the same. She didn't make us, but she said she didn't believe in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You told me you had jobs to do in the house even when you were a little girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh I used to wash pots up and - and this brothe
r fetch coal in, we all used to help me mother. And making the beds and all like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What were your jobs, washing up and making beds, did you have anything else you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, if you see like as bits - of job wants doing - I - I'll do
 that for your mother. You know, we'd go and say, can I do that mother? If she wasn't you know - getting bits of things out way. My husband - back of my cupboard when I lived over in grow, I - had all girls at home you know, only just married - and he got
 
hold of paint one day - I asked Annie it were to wash up. But her forgot. He get's cupboard door wide open, gets a piece of chalk inside, and he put - Elsie so - such a day. Alice such a day. And he fetched coal up, that only lad I had, he had to run erra
n
ds, all - all wrote down, now he says, you'll not fall out next time, look behind that cupboard, he says, it shows you what you've got to do. Your mother's here on her own. She's cooking and doing for all lot of us, there's seven on us, he says, and being
 out, he says, and she's out looking for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 Jo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
ck, not locked, I didn't - to go shopping all over. And then he'd say, no falling out, there's your job there. Oh he's strict with 'em. Very strict with 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you left school and started going to work did you still have to help your mother at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh aye, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your brothers and sister also have to help as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Aye. You'd a job to do at home, yes. Because she'd a lot on you know with men you know, cooking and doing for 'em, they brough
t their stuff and whatnot in, she had to do to make ends meet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your elder brothers help the little ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 My sister - was only young girl, a bit older, but I can remember her - and that were when we lived down Beryl Street at Mexborough. And 
- no, it wasn't - yes, it were down Beryl - no - Beryl Street at Rotherham, and she weren't very old and she laid thirteen months on her back. She'd typhoid fever. And - she were laid under mother's window - under window like - and she were laid there for
 
thirteen month, and they had feather pillows under her. This is me sister what's living now. Bedridden, and she laid there thirteen months and - we daren't put - tell you the truth we daren't hardly move her, she was like a bag of bones. But them days the
y
 never took 'em away. At hospital, kept 'em at home. Well she laid under window. And she developed pneumonia. There were both of us, I got typhoid at same time. Yes, I had typhoid - no I hadn't, but I had pneumonia. She developed that. We both got it toge
ther, but she were worse than me. And just - she looked like a doll. I never forget that, no. And mother sat up night and day, lads like with her, taking their time with her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 The boys took their turn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, to sit up with me dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 They all took turns?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. And then we had to have a boil - a steamy kettle, window open }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 for}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 to get us breath. Eeh and we had a do that time, I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you think this is why you have your bronchial now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 My bronchial come when I first 
come to Keighley. I developed it then, yes. You see, where we come from - there were no - practically no smoke, no - nor no mills nor nothing like that. As soon as I come here there's all these chimneys going and that - and that's what caused this. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 Sometimes it's worse than others, but doctor's attitude there's no cure for it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
He says you can get ease, but it turns into asthma. Sometimes I think mine will do and all because - I get sometimes right out of wind, you see, I'm frightened to death - I'm not frightened but sometimes just caches me you know, when I'm walking to shop.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you were children were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes. About half past seven at night. Never up - never up late. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well sometime me mother used to but of course we were getting on we could put ourselves to bed, you know, we used to go to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How old would you be when you started putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh about - seven year old, something like that - between that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you were at Beryl Street did you share your bedroom with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes, with me sister. Me and me sister sleep in a room to ourself. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you have a double bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, we had a bed - a little single bed a piece.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How did the whole family sleep, did the brothers have a room of their own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, they had a room - of their own, and me and me sister had a little room of us own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 And your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Where did the lodgers sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Well - there was - three brothers in one room, me mother and father another room, and the biggest room, that was over 't' - over dining - not dining room - kitchen, in the front - I call them front rooms you know. Well the lodg
er slept in there. And there were three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What room did you used to bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 We had a bathroom downstairs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You had a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, as well, yes. Put up }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6165473\charrsid12200121 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  the kitchen, like - say this were house well - here - was a door, that was go into bathroom. Well it was - it was practically new house, nobody else lived in it. We were first to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  in, me mother died in there, me father died in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You must have been quite unusual at that time to have your own bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. It was a b
athroom. But - it were more like a - a zinc thing. Weren't like one of these what there is now, it were kind of a - shape of one but it like - not aluminum but zinc, like a zinc affair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But it had running water, it had taps attached to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes, there were taps, had tap on, but there were no surroundings on it. So it weren't blocked in, it was just - yes. Yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How often would you have a bath at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh when we wanted one, we used to go and drop in, any warm weather we used to go nearly every night. Me and our Lizzie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 How often would you have clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Well - used to always put clean on at Sunday. And then - mother used to wash at Thursday, well sometimes she used to wash at Sunday, and hang 'em out you know
 - you know with only having like her to do lot and then at Thursday we used to change ourself again. Then she'd wash 'em up at Sunday, you see. To leave us clean on again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh in the living room. In kitchen - in the kitchen - house like, and then there were little room that went through passage. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Were there any occasions when you had your meal in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well it - it - no, we all had it in kitchen what were in home, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
She had a - she had a - now what do you call it - in't' kitchen - she had like a - a washer boiler, them boilers what they - well she - copper, like a copper but it weren't - not like them, it were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 built}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  in wall, it were copper and it used }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 - open the little door open, lid like, and then they used to put coal in it underneath. And then she had a big boiler over top of that. And she used to have a gas ring, big - a two way gas ring. And she used to put - she had oven in fireplace. An
d old fashioned -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 A fire range?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, with a big shelf on top like and a big oven to hold a - oh, eight loaves. Ordinary fire grate you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you were at school what time would you have breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you know what time - in the mo
rning before I went to school? Used to get up early with me mother. Well - we'll say around about half past eight. Before I went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would you be all there for your breakfast, your mother, father and all the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What about your father and the lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
And me young brothers - youngest brother, used to be always something - always black us shoes before we went to - before we went to bed and black us shoes and put them - he had to do. He used to - father us
ed to say to him, come on Thomas, get down here to this brush. Get your boots clean for school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 That was his job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Aye, it were his job that. Fetching coal up out of cellar. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You and the other children would have your breakfast about half past eight in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What about your father and the lodgers, what time would they have their breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well me dad, he used to get up when he wanted, you know, him not being well, he never kept well, and he used to get
 up and sometime mother'd take him a mug of tea up. He'd say, I'll g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
t up in a bit our Alice, he used to say to her. She never used to bother him much you know. His rheumatics in all legs, his legs you know. But they had to get up early to go to work the l
odgers, two of 'em. But the old gentleman as I told you about, well he couldn't go to work you see. There's one knee, right - oh a right cripple he was. He were - he were with mother about twelve year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did he have his breakfast with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, the
y send their breakfast - we used to get up and get the lodgers breakfasts ready and he used to get up and he would say sometimes, I don't want nowt to eat this morning ma, I'll have a drink of tea. He weren't a big eater. But t'others'd get up, what they 
w
anted cooking they'd leave it out night afore and then me mother, she used to do it in the morning when she used to call 'em up, she used to have alarum and put alarum on for 'em and then used to get up and then breakfast'd be ready for 'em when they come
 down. Just that and a - and a bed at night. And they had their own - all their own jobs, she couldn't do it. But they weren't much trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 It sounds as if your father was off work quite a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh aye. Ever since he left steel works. He fell poorly then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would that be after you got married that he started to be poorly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, afore.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Was he working when you were still at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So would he get up with the lodgers and have his breakfast early at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Sometimes he would, it just depended how he felt like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What sort of a breakfast would you have in those days? What would your mother make for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well it just depends what they brought in you see. They used to bring the stuff in theirselves,
 had their own stuff. And they'd say, ma, will you cook this for breakfast in morning. Might be - a slice of ham or - couple of boiled eggs or something like that. And they'd leave it out for me mother to do it next morning for 'em to get up. She were use
d to a way of her own you know, she were used to having them, 'cos she'd know ropes round you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What would you and your brothers and sister have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well - we never have none of this 'ere Weetabix or nowt like that. We had to have o
ur oat - oat porridge, you know oatmeal porridge. And our grandson, he still has it now. Aye, lives down in Kent. He won't go to school without he got his porridge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You used to have porridge before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I used to like - yes, used 
to like me porridge. Sometimes I'll have a slice of toast, sometimes mother'd cook us a bit of something for our breakfast, a bit of bacon, make us a sandwich with that. We never went without jock. Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would you have anything special on Sunday morning for breakfast? Would you have bacon and egg or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Aye. Yes, yes. At Sunday morning we always had bacon and egg at Sunday morning. Yes. Some had 'em boiled that didn't want 'em fried you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What did you used to call your midday meal, did you call it dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Yes. Well - sometimes - when you feel hungry about - round about half past two or three o'clock, I'd go to me mother, I'd say, have you got a biscuit mum? Can't you wait for your tea? You know. No, I said, I fe
el a bit hungry. Well she give me a couple of biscuits, shut me up while me tea, she won't make me tea for me. I'll have to make that serve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 At dinner times did you have your dinners at school or did you come home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. They - they - me sister did. And she had to pay five shillings a week for my sister. Yes. Aye, yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But you used to go home for your dinner did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh - no I used to take - sometimes I'd take a sandwich with me and then - get a - sometimes I'd have it at school, j
ust depends when I feel fit. You could have it any time you wanted you see, not - like they are now like and - we had to pay for it. Yes, so much a day. Just depends what we had, yes. Me - me - me sister - no she didn't pay five shilling - she paid that f
ive shilling to go to this school. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 That was the fee to send your sister to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. That was in Rotherham. It were Alma Road Board School where I went to. And me husband went there. Me sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So you and your brothers went to school and you used to buy sandwiches for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Yes. And probably - probably - same as - we went dinner time to have us dinner. It perhaps wouldn't be ready, well it's not ready, you'll have to wait. Well we couldn't wait, we're going back to school
. And she said, wait. I said, no, I it'll be too late by time you get it done, 'cos she were back - she were back late - going shopping and she got it late for it to - to be done. And she'd say, well, come here, she said, and have this sandwich, or have a
 
sandwich then I'll make you a hot tea when you come home. Something like that if she were a bit busy or - especially when she's washing you know, sometimes she'd wash at - well I used to help her - wash at night time, get 'em all right - ready for morning
. Then she'd hang 'em all out to dry. Oh we always helped her, aye, always - all lot of us, we all did a bit for me mother. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So at dinner time it was what you could catch more or less?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 If your mother had time she'd make your meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 But if she hadn't you'd have sandwiches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 That's right. We always had a good tea when - yes, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What did your father and the lodgers do for their midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh they'd get their dinner but you see they could wait for 
theirs. We had to go back to school you see. Sometimes she wouldn't have it done and - poor old Bobby used to say, oh don't bother about me ma. I'll have it later on. You can't be in and out - to run up and down for it. 'Cos she were getting to age, getti
ng on then you know. Oh she worked hard for us. A good mother. One of the best.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What about on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh we had fine dinner at Sunday. Yes, 'cos we were all there to help you see. One of 'em did potatoes and t'other -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What sort of a meal would it be at dinner time on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well - sometimes there'd be roast - roast beef and potatoes and cabbage and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 Yorkshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  pudding and all like that. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would you have a sweet as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes, if we wanted one, got a bit of rice puddi
ng or - oh she'd have a good meal, we all got a good jock. Good job I did, I think I couldn't have stood what I've stood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You say your mother often made you a hot tea, what sort of a tea would you have when you got home from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well sometim
es me mother'd bake some, and she'd say, do you want some - she used to ask us 'cos - were funny at times over us meals - she'd say, do you want some of this Alice? Oh no, I don't fancy none of that mum today. Tell you what, do us two slices of toast. I'd
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 have}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 that. And I - I enjoy it. Or I'd have - sometimes she'd make a - and she could bake - sometimes she'd make a big apple pie and a big custard in a - in a big round tin, and the crust were that thick, just a bit of crust on, I used to love that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Wh
en you'd been home at dinner time and she hadn't had time to make you a dinner and she said I'll make you a hot tea, what would it be for a hot tea do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Well sometimes it'd be a - a jam }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 roly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  pudding boiled, you know, something like that. And
 then potatoes and sometimes it'd be chips and egg. Have what you wanted. You'd get what you wanted, if you didn't fancy it you get what you want. On no, wouldn't let you go without, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Would your father be back from the steelworks at teatime when you had yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Oh no, we used to have us tea afore they come in. Me and me mother - us two, me sister, we used to have us tea and be done with and the table was all set ready for them coming in for their tea, you see. They all sit down together, make one meal of it.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What did the lodgers do about their dinner and tea, did they have it out somewhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Yes, they'd take sandwiches. And then they'd have a - a can of tea or a mug of tea you know when they're out, well like they do now, do the same now on building site you know. Well }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 they'd}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 have a - cut some sandwiches up and then when they get home their wives makes 'em hot dinner. You see, potatoes and - I used to do that for my lad when he worked at Cullingworth. He were not working well - there w
ere nowhere up there he could go for a meal you see. Well they were forced to take sandwiches. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 
And then when he come home I used to make him a good potato pie or something like that potato pie, oh aye.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did your mother of father bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. I baked - I baked two stone afore I come here. I did. My husband }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 won
\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  eat a slice of bread - bread from shop. Do you know what he used to say? He used to say, it's idleness of - yes. There used to be a little shop at roadside when I lived up at 
Whitehorse and - she used to make all her buns and bread up, they were lovely, and one time he were poorly with - Victoria with water troubles and she used to bring him - he'd say - about that big - and she used to bring him one about every - see he didn'
t
 - weren't a big bread eater but - he used to love it. He said, I can't eat that shop bread. She always used to bring it up but wouldn't take a ha'penny off me. She said, oh Mrs Scroop, I know how you are she said, it's all right. Oh, I said, I'd sooner p
ay you, I said. I let little things like that play on me mind. It were good of her and she used to always bring him this loaf. They were good to him, the missus at Whitehorse was.
