\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did we what luv?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, used to read to theirselves, used to go and sit in room and read to theirself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember a funeral in the family before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 1918. In my family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember perhaps a grandma or a grandpa?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Yes. My Ernest's mother. My husband's mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She died before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She'd have been - a hundred if she'd have lived two - St Patrick's Day. Seventeenth of March. She'd have been a hundred. 
She died in Rotherham - what they used to call the work house then. I lived at Mexborough. She lived with me three year, and then she become to be funny, you know, get queer, and she used to smoke, you know, old Irish woman. She used to smoke. She used to
 
go out at nighttime you know, I used to know what time she went out. And - she come over a bit late. It's always been afore seven o'clock, or just turned seven. So I says to me husband, I said, your mother's not come yet. Well nobody'd else-d have her, on
l
y me. So, anyway - she says - he says, she's not in, I says, no. He says, well she - hope nowt happened to her. So - she used to like a gill of beer you know at night time. So I - I said I think I know where she is, she's in Commercial. So I went out, I w
as going to have a look for her as I went out. 'Cos I used to say to her, now look - don't go no far away 'cos I get worried you being out, getting knocked down. But she never did. She were careful. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 So, anyway I was look in this public, and it stood back, I can see it now, stood back at top of Hope Street, and there were two steps, and there were a little snicket. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh it weren't as big as this, and there were about four in there. Four old women. I shall never forget. See I just went like that. Looking up. Com
e on, it's bedtime. I said, I've been worried to death over you, I says, I says wondering where you was. But she never stopped out before, she was always in bed for - they were all four having a packet of chips and fish. All of them, all the lot of them h
a
d a packet of fish. Who ever fetched 'em I don't know, 'cos they were all us for a god age. Tell you she were a hundred just in St Patrick's Day. I said, come on. She'd got her glass of beer. She come out, she come out, I gets hold of her arm, says, come 
on we'll walk across the road now. I lived at the back of the Empire. A picture place. I said, do you know you frightened me to death. She said, what's up, I told you were in Commercial, she said. I said, I'm not getting on to you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 Gran}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  I says, I says, but i
t's - you've never stopped out late before, I says, and you made me right uncomfortable, thought something had happened to you. She said, no, she says, so anyway - she says, I've been out a bit, having chips and fish. I said, well you could have some at h
o
me. She said, oh I'd sooner have 'em out like that myself, fancy 'em better. Anyway she got in trouble when I got home. He says, where the hell have - he were right snotty with - I said, don't shout at her. So, he says, where have you been, She says, what
 
- who wants to know? What do you want to know for? She was haughty - right haughty with him you know. So - anyway - he says, well you frightened Alice to death, he says. You never stop out late like this. So she said, well if that wants to know, I've had 
a gill of beer, and me chips and fish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She'd had a good night out hadn't she?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I said I didn't mind, I - I said you all live around with pub in back streets and that. Mm. Yes, it told lass.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So I think by the time she died it would be after 1918 would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 She died while I were at Mexborough, I lived in Mexborough. Oh we left in 1918. Me husband were at home and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember anyone in your family or in your husband's family dying before the end of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Before the end of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you have any grandparents? On either side?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh no, I don't - I don't remember - they never talked about 'em. I mean she had one sister in America.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When Fred died, would that be before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh that would be, that, yes. But I had another brother died, but it wasn't in war time. It was after 19 - 18. Our George.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember Fred dying? And the funeral afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No. No, I don't remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You can't remember whether there was people going to it or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, I've forgot that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 And when your other brother died it would be after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Yes, our George. But - me eldest brother died first. Our Fred died first, that were it, and me oldest brother, he died - he's dead. And next to him
, our George, he died in Sheffield hospital. And me youngest brother - still is older than me if you understand. And I've never heard from him - in years and years and years, and he were older than me so I should think he might have passed out, I don't kn
ow. He lost his wife. Lived with his daughter, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 So you can't remember a funeral before 1918 can you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 That were the last world war weren't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Before the end of the first world war?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Hang on, the end of the first world war? 1916?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Any time between 1900 and 1918. Any time during that period. I wondered if as a little girl you'd been to a funeral at all? Usually it would stand out in your mind if you had been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, I've - I've only one - buried one little girl, and she were three week old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I wondered if when you were a little girl you'd been to a funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Oh yes, I went to a funeral but - I just forget the name now, I were a bearer for a little girl. A bearer when I lived - lived in Orchard Street then, I weren't ver
y old. And me and Annie Aldrid - it just come to me that name, Annie Aldrid and we were right big friends together and we were bearers - used to have little girls for bearers for 'em them days, yes. Well I were a bearer. I can remember that now you come t
o
 talk about it. And - this little girl had died. I can't just think of her name. And - when we come back they give us a drop of port wine. It made me poorly. The first time I'd ever - tasted it. And - oh it upset me. Felt poorly many a day after it. And I
 said I'd never drink no more, and I never have. And she weren't very old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 What was it she died from, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, I don't know what she died from but they come and asked me mother - if I could be a bearer. And Annie Olden - and - an Irish gi
rl - there were three of us. Remember Annie Olden getting married, she married my husband's mate. But I don't know - whether they could have called him Ted Tuckman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you were a bearer at this funeral did you have to wear all black?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh yes. U
sed to wear a - we used to wear a sash, a black sash round us. Bear - bearer, carry 'em on your shoulders like - yes, she weren't very big. A love - lovely little kiddie. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You said you went back for a drink of port wine, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 was there}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  a sort of gathering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No, they - they brought - we come - when we come back - we went into }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 
house like}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  you do and sit down you know, they come round with this drop of port wine in a glass. And I says to Annie - I says, what's this? You know, 'cos we didn't know what d
rink were you know, we weren't very old. And I thought this - what's this? I don't know. So, one of the women, I just forget what - who it were - Mrs Marras they call her, Mara, Murray, Murray, and - she says, what are you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 whispering}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  at you two? I says, wh
at is it Mrs Murray? She says, port wine, she says, get it down you, could do you good, it'll warm you. And it happened to have been a cold day and we were very damp. But anyway - it upset me for a day or two. Says it's perhaps with - not having any like 
you know it's just - touched - the tickled spot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you were a little girl were you taken out visiting neighbours or friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 You never were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Were you ever taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Oh with me mother, used to g
o with me mother at Saturday. Take me to market every Saturday. And me cat. Me cat. Me cat used to follow us to market. Sit on wall side while we come back. Aye. With butchers and all, fresh meat. I can remember that. I weren't very old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Very rare I went with him luv.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
I can remember going to a theatre with him. When he used to come from work he used to go to a certain public, I'll tell you the truth, and he used to like
 his pint of beer, that was when he could work then, and - it were a public called Feathers, Prince of Wales Feathers, and that's where he used to go every Friday night and that's where I used to get me mother's half a sovereign from. And he used to call 
i
n for a pint before he come home. And me mother used to say - go on Alice, go on your - journey else I won't get me half a sovereign. And he used to give me half - half a sovereign for me mother. Mind he was a good fellow in one way, but he never believed
 in giving her a lot of money. It's because she had the lodgers you see. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 He knew she could manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Yes. That's right, yes. So - anyway he'd say, come on, sit down, you could sit down with 'em them days, and you used to have a bottle - bot - bottle what - I used to take to work for him. And - I said, have you took your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 bottle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  - did it go down all right dad? Says, aye. He says, wait while I sup }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3884354\charrsid12200121 this}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121  pint. He says, we're going to theatre. I said, where? Theatre, he says, Lower Road - down by the
 Manchester, picture - plays, olden days you know. Same as the Good Old Days what's on telly, you know. I says, come on then. And - he'd take his bottle and put it in his pocket, be empty you know, and there used to be a public at bottom of road, used to 
c
all it - Monarch, the Monarch, and go up the street, go straight up the side of the hospital, and - anyway we went to see theatre. Come on half time, come on like two turns. They'd go in at half past seven and at eight o'clock change over, it was about ha
l
f past eight when we come out there was different turns on. And anyway he used to say, come on Alice, they pulled sheet down for ten minutes, go and fetch me three gills of beer down at the Monarch. And I used to fetch him three gills of beer. And used to
 
put us a - a slip on top like a - a label, label on top 'cos you weren't old enough, that's how young I was, and they put a label on top. And they said, what do you want? Three gills of dark beer. Go back, run for your life down to bottom, but I enjoyed i
t
 because I were at theatre and got mother's half a quid. So I went down, bring bottle back, do you want a sup of the pint. I says, get off. So I said, well, I said, no I don't want your stinking beer. I said, it stinks to it never forget. We went again. A
n
d they were all looking round, they wondered what he'd got in bottle, you know look round. And we used to watch these theatres does. The old man of Manchester, all such like as that, oh yes. Mind it took a while, nearly ten o'clock when I come out, quarte
r }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 to ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
 we used to come out. Then we'd come straight home. So - mother says I - poor old mother, she'd say, has he give you me half a sovereign? I said, I have it mother. Aye. But - and that's all she ever got, my mother. I remember it as if it were - I've
 a good memory. Mm. I've a lass like that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 My eldest is like that, taked after me for - good educated, she's never been nowhere. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Just picked it up on her own. Mm. Good lass.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember any outings with your parents, perhaps at Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Have I what luv?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Do you remember any outings that you went on with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Out - out? Visiting? Outings you mean? Oh yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 
Oh yes, I've - well I took - me two children - I've two children christened at Arm - at Salvation Army, under flag
, And I were big Army woman meself then, I used to go regular, I used to like Army, and we used to go - what they call across the Ferry, in a boat. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
And it used to be a penny to go across. And it was across then we used to go all the way round like going round lakes you know - in the boat. And I had two were christened under flag there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2580133\charrsid12200121 
Had our Ena and our Alice.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 When you were a little girl yourself did your parents used to take you on this boat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 I used to go to Army then. No, no. I went with the Army, used to take us you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Can you remember any occasions when your parents took you out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Oh no. I never went out much myself. No. I always stuck to me mother like to help me mother. We were - all our mother's family if you understand. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3230341 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 Did you ever go away for a holiday when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1009002 AS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
Well - when the - when me brother - our Thomas you know worked at steel trade - and works for it - there used to be tickets - they used to give 'em tickets, and they'd go to - they co
uld take anybody with it, give 'em a free ticket to take anybody with 'em - we did that. I know me dad took me and our Joe. And - and Joe, and we went to New Brighton. And we got to New Brighton, and I went across - across in boat, and we was going, makin
g
 us way to Sunlight Soap Works. Sunlight Soap Works there you know. And we never got - managed to go. Well they'd been and had a drink, they got tired, got sleepy, gets across to the - river, and got sat down onto grass, and they fell fast asleep and left
 
me there with meself. And there's a fellow there coming on with a donkey. Yes. So he bought me some mussels, and I was eating my mussels when they wakened up. So we didn't land - we didn't land to - we didn't land at soap work Sunlight works so - so - mea
