Well happen me bro - youngest brother, Thomas. He was a - he - he was a lovely lad, well they were all three of 'em. And our George were a gentleman, him that died in Sheffield. Wasn't married. And - that youngest - he were - you
 - he were next to our George - our - our Thomas was youngest and - he had a - he had a kind of a stroke in his face and it was - like that, but last time I heard from him it's gone all right, but it's a long while since, it's gone back, grown back, and -
 
he neither drinks nor smokes. They're all - they don't like a lot, just have a - now him that died, this tall one, our George - if you had a - went in and he'd got a bottle of stout he'd make it last an hour. They weren't big drinkers. No. Me dad was a bi
g
 drinker but he liked a drink at night time. But mother never touched. It bothered me mother nothing. She used to say you can have a barrelful as long as you - don't fall out, she didn't like falling out with anybody. She were a good living woman my mothe
r was
