ere never anybody come to see you after midwife had finished you see. But - anyway, if she - if she saw you couldn't feed it - do you think you'll be able to feed it Mrs Scroop? I says, well, I says - I'll have to give it chance you see, to draw milk. I s
ays, as a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2714250\charrsid12200121 rule}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
, I said - I - I've always fed my children. Except our Nellie. Well our Nellie, that's the second oldest girl that's living - well - when I was carrying her - and me sister, me sister weren't married then, she were living - with my mother like
, and - oh aye, she was - no, she weren't married. And we both be down with this here bad - oh and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2714250\charrsid12200121 diphtheria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10504500\charrsid12200121 
, they were taking them away with dozens. This is when they took us away. Me and my children. And - yes, 'cos it's gone now. Oh I were going to tel
l you. So any rate it were all in my throat, and all in me sister's back, me mother had both of us down with this, so anyway - oh I couldn't swallow me own spittle like. So when doctor come he says - told me mother, he says - is very poorly is Alice, and 
