days. And - I had it all in me throat and I thought I were going to choke I tell you and - that's when I inhaled this here - yes, Friar's Balsam. And - then he come the next morning, and he saw what I were like, well he told - he told - midwife - me siste
r
 having called, he kept a public house which was somewhere around, she used to do - I used to go and clean for her a bit you know now and again, and anyway - she - oh when she come in the morning - and I didn't live there then, I lived on - Sheffield Road
.
 In rooms on there, we couldn't get a house for love nor money then. And - when she come all morning, it were third morning, no it wasn't, it were the next morning, she were born at day before, and I says, oh listen at our babby, Mrs Standby. She said, wh
a
t's the matter Alice? I said, oh, she's making a funny noise. I says - she's - you'd think she was having - drawing a pint of milk way she's going at it. And she never had a drink. And she kept going - and I thought, well I've never had any kiddie - you k
n
ow, making them funny noises, I've never had 'em. So anyhow I told her of it, well so - she got this spoon and - put it in our babby's mouth. And - holded it down. And - right down into her throat, yes. And - she had two - what they call two - cracks, lit
