le cracks you know. Well she'd two instead of one. Yes. And she had to - it was with me coughing and - me throat, it had split, and it were shape of a lemon here, like - well like an egg like that, it were open. And anyway I never felt that - I never felt
 
nowt but anyway - nurse - She had to going to - going to - you know, when she got to going to school - well started mimicking her at school, calling her to talk right, this that and the other. Well it grieved me and it grieved our Nellie. She used to cry 
e
very time she come home, I thought well, I'm not having this. So I kept her away, that - school policeman come down. Now Mrs Scroop, what's the matter with Nellie, she's not at school? I said, well - I said, well, I said, she's not fit to go to school, I 
s
aid, I'm not going to let her go - to be called after, she's deficient in her throat. So anyway, so I report this. So her put her down to clinic. So I went down to clinic - I took her and it were - he said, now Mrs Scroop what about Ellen? I says, well, I
 
says, the reason I've let her go to school, I said, 'cos it's shameful how they're calling after her. She says, can't you get it at hospital? She says, no. So she says, for why? I says, well I've a - me husband off poorly, I says, that's he nearly had his
 
fingers nearly taken off in pit and they won't give you a recommend when they're not in work. Oh, she says, it's a funny place. Said, you leave it to me she says, I'll get her in hospital. So I says - I'll see what your husband says, and I'll drop you a l
